//19. Remove Nth Node From End of List
//Given the head of a linked list, remove the nth node from the end of the list and return its head.
//Example 1:
//Input: head = [1,2,3,4,5], n = 2
//Output: [1,2,3,5]
//Example 2:
//Input: head = [1], n = 1
//Output: []
//Example 3:
//Input: head = [1,2], n = 1
//Output: [1]


Brute Force Approach -> (Find Length First)

class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* removeNthFromEnd(ListNode* head, int n) {
        int length = 0;
        ListNode* curr = head;
        while(curr) {
            length++;
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        // Remove the head
        if(length == n) {
            return head->next;
        }
        int position = length - n;
        curr = head;
        for(int i = 1; i < position; i++) {
            curr = curr->next;
        }
        curr->next = curr->next->next;
        return head;
    }
};

Intuition ->

First, find the length of the linked list.
The node to remove is:
(position = length - n + 1)
from the beginning.
Traverse again until reaching the node just before it,
then bypass the target node.

Complexity Analysis ->
Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes
Reason:
One traversal to calculate the length.
One traversal to remove the node.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
Only a few pointer variables are used.

------------------------------------------------------------

Optimal Approach -> (Two Pointers + Dummy Node)

class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* removeNthFromEnd(ListNode* head, int n) {
        ListNode* dummy = new ListNode(0);
        dummy->next = head;
        ListNode* slow = dummy;
        ListNode* fast = dummy;
        // Create a gap of n + 1 nodes
        for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
            fast = fast->next;
        }
        while(fast) {
            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next;
        }
        slow->next = slow->next->next;
        return dummy->next;
    }
};

Intuition ->

Maintain a gap of (n + 1) nodes between the fast and slow pointers.

Move the fast pointer first.

Then move both pointers together.

When fast reaches NULL,

slow will be exactly one node before the node that must be removed.

Simply bypass that node.

A dummy node is used so that removing the head becomes a normal case instead of a special case.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)

where:
n = number of nodes

Reason:
The linked list is traversed only once.

Space Complexity -> O(1)

Reason:
Only a few pointer variables are used.

